 saw a surge in humorous entertainment in both democratic and authoritarian societies. The Politics of Humour examines how works such as satirical magazines and comedy films were used both to reaffirm group identity and to exclude those who did not belong.The essays in this collection analyse the political and social context of comedy in Europe and the United States, exploring topics ranging from the shifting targets of ethnic jokes to the incorporation of humour into wartime broadcasting and the uses of satire as a means of resistance. Comedy continues to define the nature of group membership today, and The Politics of Humour offers an intriguing look at how entertainment helped everyday people make sense of the turmoil of the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAmerican wit and humorxHistory and criticism. 0aEuropean wit and humorxHistory and criticism. 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Humor.2bisacsh1 aBrook, Vincent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGillooly, Eileen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJelavich, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKessel, Martina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKuipers, Giselinde, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMerziger, Patrick , eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMerziger, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPater, Monika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWinokur, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144269512240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442695122423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/978